<br>
But the interesting thing is the umpire had no clue. He heard chainlink the guy who hit it deaked and stopped at second. Saying to the umpire it was a double. So the umpire basically took his word for it. Not having seen the ball or the second chainlink fence 20 feet behind the first. Dude I was in the outfield. It was gone by plenty, not even close. <br>
<br>
This happened in the second game of the finals. To basically end the night. Maybe I am wrong but it seems to me that the team in full uni's with the huge camper in the parking lot who are supposed to win always get the close call when they play the put-togethers/scrubs in with 5 different colored shirts. No matter how well we are playing. <br>
<br>
The better team probably won but hell I would have liked to played that last inning. Especially with a couple of homers left. By no means did this ruin a great tourney but it wasn't even close. Our RF ran into the fence on the play. Even a blind man knew it was a home run. Lets just say I had a few choice words for him. And believe me if the homeplate umpire didn't know I was right he would have tossed me because I dropped about 15 f bombs for the world to hear. But that is part of it. The ump behind the plate knew he was wrong and would not change it. <br>
